The paper discusses the use of conjugate gradient methods for data detection and precoding in massive MIMO systems, which are typically studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The paper also proposes a novel way of computing the post-equalization signal-to-interference-and-noise-ratio (SINR), which falls under the signal processing (cs.SI) sub-category. The use of soft-output minimum mean-square error (MMSE) detection and the investigation of performance/complexity trade-offs suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the machine learning (cs.LG) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories.
